    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "valgrind isn't really a great option for us because our target hardware is a bare-metal environment with very limited resources. we can't run a heavy profiler like that on the actual unit. are there any specific patterns or common C++ pitfalls in embedded systems that usually cause these kinds of slow, creeping leaks? like, specifically with how we might be handling buffers or dynamic allocation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In the absence of Valgrind, you can focus on common C++ pitfalls in embedded systems. One common cause of memory leaks is the use of global variables, which can lead to memory fragmentation and unpredictable behavior. You should also be cautious when using static variables or static arrays, as they can cause memory to be allocated and not immediately deallocated. Additionally, be mindful of the use of `new` and `delete` operators, as manual memory management can lead to memory leaks if not done correctly. \n\nAnother possibility is that your buffer management might be incorrect, such as not properly initializing or freeing buffers, or using the wrong type of buffer (e.g., using a stack-allocated buffer for a heap-allocated allocation). \n\nIt's also worth looking into the use of `std::unique_ptr` and `std::shared_ptr` which can help manage dynamic memory and prevent leaks.",
      "source": "target",
